{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:30:58.790464", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — Clos topology (EBGP)\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall control-plane (BGP) appears converged and routes for all /24 host subnets are present on the routers. Routing tables and BGP tables across super-spine, spine and leaf routers show the expected /24 prefixes.\n- The primary data-plane anomaly is that host pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) is intermittently or wholly unreachable from many other hosts. Multiple end-to-end pings to 10.0.1.2 fail or are unknown. Neighbor leaf router (leaf_router_0_1) sees packet loss reaching the host, and the host’s interface is in a DOWN state with dropped packets recorded.\n- Fault is localized to the access segment for 10.0.1.0/24: either pc_0_1 itself (its NIC / OS state) or the link between pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1. There is no evidence of a fabric-wide routing/advertisement problem for the 10.0.1.0/24 prefix.\n\nDetailed observations (evidence)\n\n1) Reachability matrix (summary):\n- Many origin hosts show status \"unknown\" when dst = 10.0.1.2 (pc_0_1) in the aggregated reachability results.\n- Direct ping test from pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1 timed out (ping_pair timed out).\n- leaf_router_0_1 -> pc_0_1 returned 4 transmitted, 2 received (50% packet loss).\n- leaf_router_0_0 -> pc_0_1 timed out on our test.\n- Other host-to-host traffic (between other /24s) was successful (0% loss) in the reachability dataset.\n\n2) pc_0_1 local network status (get_host_net_config):\n- ifconfig output for pc_0_1 eth0 shows: flags=4098<BROADCAST,MULTICAST> — interface is DOWN (not UP).\n- ip_addr shows eth0 in state DOWN but with inet 10.0.1.2/24 configured.\n- ifconfig counters show RX packets 18 but RX dropped 17 and TX packets only 2 — significant dropped RX, very little transmitted traffic.\n\n3) leaf_router_0_1 local state:\n- leaf_router_0_1 has 10.0.1.1/24 assigned on its access interface (eth4) and kernel route: 10.0.1.0/24 dev eth4 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.1.1.\n- leaf_router_0_1’s routing table shows it knows all host /24s via BGP (it is advertising/learning the prefixes); 10.0.1.0/24 is locally attached on leaf_router_0_1 (C>* 10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected).\n- leaf_router_0_1 -> pc_0_1 test returned 50% loss (2/4 replies).\n\n4) BGP / routing (control plane):\n- BGP tables on super-spine, spines and leaves show the 10.0.x.0/24 and 10.1.x.0/24 networks are present and appear to be propagated across ASes as expected.\n- Leaves have the correct kernel-connected route for their local /24 and BGP entries for remote /24s. No broad BGP convergence issue visible in the collected outputs.\n\n5) Other notes:\n- A ping from super_spine_router_0 to the leaf link IP reported \"Network is unreachable\" in the test output. This is a separate symptom related to reachability to specific point-to-point 172.16.x.x /31 link addresses and does not contradict the fact that the /24 host prefixes are present in the routing tables. It appears that the super-spine has no route to that specific link address — likely because P2P link addresses are not advertised/needed across EBGP in this lab configuration. This is informational and not the main cause of the host-level outage.\n\nAnomalies identified\n1) Host interface state anomaly: pc_0_1 eth0 is DOWN (interface flags indicate not UP) while still having an IP configured and showing many dropped RX packets.\n2) Packet-loss / reachability anomaly: intermittent / partial reachability to 10.0.1.2 (50% packet loss seen from leaf_router_0_1; many sources could not reach it at all).\n3) Some testing attempts to P2P link addresses from super-spine returned \"Network is unreachable\" — likely expected in this environment, but worth noting.\n\nFault localization (most likely to least likely)\n- Primary: pc_0_1 (host) and/or its immediate link:\n  - Evidence: eth0 is DOWN on pc_0_1, RX dropped counters are high, direct pings to the host time out, leaf router sees packet loss when pinging the host.\n  - Likely point of failure: NIC administratively down, driver/OS issue on pc_0_1, or a physical/link-layer problem on the host side (virtual NIC disconnect, cable/VNIC attachment, or port down).\n- Secondary (less likely but possible): access link / port on leaf_router_0_1:\n  - Evidence: leaf_router_0_1 can reach some hosts and has the 10.0.1.0/24 directly configured; it observed partial reachability to pc_0_1 (so the router’s access interface is up). If the host's interface is flapping, the leaf-side port might also be flapping or seeing carrier issues.\n- Tertiary (unlikely): BGP/control-plane fabric issue:\n  - Evidence: BGP tables are present and consistent; almost all other inter-subnet traffic works. This indicates fabric-wide routing is healthy. The issue is localized to the access segment.\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis\n- The root cause is most likely a host-level interface/link problem for pc_0_1:\n  - The host NIC appears to be down/unavailable (interface not UP) or the link to the leaf router is flapping/dropped. This causes heavy packet drops and results in many peers being unable to reach 10.0.1.2.\n  - Because the leaf router has the 10.0.1.0/24 directly connected and BGP is advertising/learning all prefixes correctly, the control plane is healthy. The failure is therefore at the edge link/host, not in BGP or the spine fabric.\n\nAdditional supporting notes\n- leaf_router_0_1’s route table and BGP table show the 10.0.1.0/24 is local and advertised — confirming the network-level advertisement is correct.\n- The super_spine ping error to a leaf link IP is likely due to absence of a route to the specific 172.16.x.x /31 address in super-spine’s routing table; this is separate and not the cause of the host outage.\n- The observed RX dropped counter (17 dropped out of 18 received) on pc_0_1 suggests the NIC is receiving frames but the OS is dropping them (or the interface is flapping); that should be investigated closely on the host/virtual NIC side.\n\nConclusion (concise)\n- Network control plane (BGP) is healthy and the fabric is carrying routes correctly.\n- The primary anomaly is host-level: pc_0_1 is effectively unreachable due to its NIC/interface or the host-to-leaf link being down or unstable. This is the most probable root cause for the observed reachability failures to 10.0.1.2.\n- Fault is localized to the access segment (pc_0_1 and/or leaf_router_0_1 access port).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 27091, "output_tokens": 3934, "total_tokens": 31025, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 4864}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2304}}}
